caption: DC Nobu is a Nogo.  Excited to get out after being locked down for a year. Wanted to try Nobu.  What a disappointment.  Took 45 minutes to get 5 pieces of sushi, 20 minutes for a drink. (Filet was very good.) And the waitress prattled on for literally 20 minutes at other tables while we all sat and waited, waited.  Want professional service, go to Bourbon or some other established high end restaurant.  DC Nobu just doesn’t cut it.

i've been to multiple Nobu spots inside the past and this location simply lacks a number of the vibes. Stopped with the aid of lately with own family and we had the seared salmon, Alaskan black cod, mushroom toban yaki with truffle.

Lovely dinner experience!  Kind of like being in the scene of a movie — it was so very trendy feeling.  Excellent sashimi and maki rolls; our cod entree was fishy and spongy — waiter took it back and off our bill (much appreciated!). Really loved the passion fruit mochi for dessert 😊

I would give this place a five star if the service was actually good. We felt unwelcome from the moment we walked in as the hostess did not even greet us when we were obviously right in front of them standing and waiting for them to say hello.  The vibe of the servers was extremely plain in a place where you’re spending a lot of money to have a good time, at least you expect good service with a good attitude from servers.  Our server was OK, not sure if he was just having a bad day or not but it seems like all servers were just run around trying to get people served and out of there, kind of a buffet style in a Chinese restaurant.   It is extremely unfortunate as the food was really good and tasty.  For us, service means a lot.
Did take out for valentines day. Expensive but worth every penny.
Food was not good at all. Not worth the wait or the price. Would I ever go back there ... probably not. Food was cold and flavorless.

Who ever thought I would get Nobu on UberEats, but it's been a crazy year. Everything was nicely packed and still managed to look good with the constraints of to-go.  Cold items do well with delivery. I ordered a side of the fried rice cubes. I'm not sure what temperature they are supposed to be, but they were not warm - they still tasted good.  The tuna was excellent! I will be ordering again and look forward to an in-person experience.
Hands down the best Asian fusion you can eat!
Excellent
Bad customer services the waiter talks to you in a rude way
The Manager Aj is professional, thoughtful and an amazing guy. Food was out of this world and service is top notch! Definitely worth the price.
One of the best of this great chain of restaurants! Enjoyed everything I tried. On the top of quality.
Not even close to Malibu Nobu, bland watered down, and not up to the Nobu name or standards. Take a pass and eat somewhere else. AND GO TO NOBU IN CALIFORNIA
Amazing. Just breathtakingly good. We were at least 20 ft away from any other customers. Beautiful food, beautiful wine. Great service.
Love LOVE LOOOOOVE THIS PLACE! Sashimi is the best I’ve ever had tested in my life!!! The Seared Salmon Karashi Sumiso from their Cold Dishes is my favorite there!
It is nice...Not many people when I visited. Food was good (2 people) however not good enough to return $$$ ($400) No drinks...
I enjoyed very much.
Nothing special
For me it wasn't worth the money.

Sooo... Nobu is definitely an experience. Their food was really savory and presentation was great!  My friends and I ordered a ton of different hot dishes and sushi combos. $300+ later we were finally full and satisfied. The mango passion fruit martini 🍸 was delicious!!  What I will say for those who don’t know anything about Nobu, it is a luxurious experience in dining with dishes meant to be shared so I wouldn’t go to this kind of restaurant if you are hungry looking for a hearty meal.  Oh, we got seated out at the patio and the patio had such a lively ambience with dim lighting!
Ambience average, food above average, cost exorbitant.
Yummy!

I have been to a couple of Nobu spots in the past and this location just lacks some of the vibes. Stopped by recently with family and we had the seared salmon, Alaskan black cod, mushroom toban yaki with truffle, Yellowtail Jalapeno, Whitefish Dry Miso, King Crab Taco, Organic greens with seared tuna and salmon sashimi, and the beef tenderloin. The cod here is amazing just like I've had in the past. The fish and skin were cooked perfectly. The beef tenderloin was so tender and buttery. The mushrooms with truffle were surprisingly amazing. Overall, food here is great just can't justify the price. Fish quality wise its the same as other top sushi spots in the area. Don't believe the hype when you break the bank here expect to still leave hungry.

I’ve been to a lot of Nobu restaurants all over the world and loved them. There’s only two I would never go back to because the fish didn’t seem fresh and the experience was sub par. This is one of them.
Ok atmosphere
Awesome customer service
OPEN FOR BUSINESS!! Now is the time to try this place! No reservation required! While it's always good to make a reservation, people who enjoy Nobu seem to be staying home...try it, you'll love it!

Having been to the Nobu in Vegas, I was excited for this place to open in DC...finally a decent sushi place, I hoped.  After the meal I was left with a feeling that they are fully relying on the name of this place with little devotion to quality of food or staff.  The unpolished service and overall lacking  experience left much to be desired.  After a $300 bill for dinner for two, I would keep your expectations low.
Great food and acceptable service. Very classless.

Absolutely can’t go wrong with a trip to Nobu! I definitely recommend visiting for “Tanoshi hour” which is their version of happy hour. They have great drink AND food deals during happy hour. I also love the great popcorn they bring around during happy hour to snack on as you’re enjoying a refreshing cucumber martini or a lovely lychee martini. You can’t beat the 2 rolls for $10 deal at happy hour as well.

This restaurant is my first choice restaurant.  Of all restaurants I know I prefere it most. I never miss an opportunity to go to visit this place. everytime  I feel like having a fair meal, this restaurant comes straightaway to my mind. extremely good and varied  food and a rich menu.great staff, and nice spirit. Also, the tariff is reasonable. I suggest this restaurant with no hesitation.
Very yummy, but a bit pricy.
Super delicious an absolute must!! A little pricey but totally worth it!!
Love this place went to ny la as well

My friend and I went for dinner as my CNY celebration away from home. From our arrival to the end of the meal, everything was impeccable. Our server was extremely friendly leading us to allow her to decide our menu for us. Each was highly recommended and I informed her that I must have the signature black cod miso. We had cocktails while waiting before the meal started. We ended with a lovely dessert. This is my 3rd NOBU and I must say that the service and food is pretty good.
Expensive but good

Food was fresh and delicious. Expect Nobu quality service. Menu is well put together. Clearly awesome date night selection. But girls or boys night out. Price point $$$$. Make sure to get a reservation.
Amazing menu and speciality sushi selections.
Best Sushi / Japanese food.  Top tier restaurant.  Modern design, great service, food is world class.
The food was delicious and the ambiance was perfect.
The happy hour food was really good , Its worth to try, I gave 4 stars cause the food potions was kinda small. But overall was great service and tasty food 👍

I went during restaurant week and did the $35 dollar prefix menu. The waiter provided drink options of bottled still or sparkling water. During my meal, I noticed others drinking tap. No biggie, but $9 for a Fiji small bottle is very over priced and when the waiter was told about this, she simply said, “Sorry. I thought I offered tap water.” Needless to say, the portion size of the appetizer, entree, and dessert was nowhere near filling. I’m very disappointed in the price point and portion size, would not recommend this place nor will I be back.
Amazing!

The food was very good and the staffs were super attentive. My mom and I came here for DC Restaurant Week and we thoroughly enjoyed our food. However, the serving size is rather small for its price tag, but I did expected that of a restaurant like Nobu. My only complain would be that the menu for DC Restaurant week is rather limited, especially for those with certain dietary restriction, to have a full Nobu experience. An increase of 5 options per course instead of 3 would be a nice touch to give customers more variety to choose from.

Designer food and drinks. Excellent prep and taste. Portions are ultimately too small. This is an excellent tasting experience, not a meal. And also not sushi. Had I understood this before I went I probably would have appreciated more. Easily a 5 star with correct expectations.
Wow, excellent
Great
There’s no wonder why this place is so well acclaimed. The food is absolutely delicious. This is our new family favorite.
Very good but small, pricey dishes. Very chic, trendy place with excellent quality. Just know what you’re getting into beforehand

(Translated by Google) Nobu Restaurant goes without definition, you go to it if it is in any city without thinking about its wonderful dishes and a beautiful atmosphere that requires a reservation to crowd the place  (Original) مطعم نوبو غني عن التعريف تذهب اليه اذا كان موجود في اي مدينه دون التفكير أطباقه رائعه واجواء جميله يتطلب حجز لازدحام المكان
Not NYC, but it's still worth it.
Excellent food and staff!
Great Aesthetics inside! Would suggest you all to make reservations before hand.

The food was aligned with the other Nobu restaurants.  The dining room felt dated. This particular Nobu in my opinion is only good for business dinners perhaps or an early dinner. No late night buzz.  Bland atmosphere even though it was busy.
Amazing but expensive

This place is overrated bc of that Drake song. Don’t get me wrong, the service is great. But the food was comparable to other much cheaper places. My favorite thing was the attentiveness of the waitress and my tomato ceviche. The salmon avocado roll and yellowtail scallion roll were mediocre. The happy hour deals are great but I could not imagine paying cull price for that after 7.
Awesome food, a little pricey.
The food is amazing n of punt, but service can be slow for no reason at times, I just want my drinks fast
So happy to get a Nobu in DC...well worth it
Honestly...just a name. Poor service. Average sushi. Go elsewhere.
Stuck up and pretentious.  Food is good but over-priced.  About as real as Kim Kardashian.
I was here for business social event so we only had hors d'oeuvres and drinks.  Both very good.  Beautiful contemporary decor. Pleasant efficient wait staff
Fantastic service. Delicious drinks. Amazing food.
Sultry bar with a nice Happy Hour. Great for a date night. A bit removed from the action so requires an Uber/Lyft to get to the rest of the city without a hike.
Amazing place! Definitely on the expensive side but totally worth it imo. Give this place a try next time your feeling fancy!
Amazing !
What an experience,  we took the server's recommendations and experienced  a wonderful array of food. Great experience and fresh food! I recommend you try it!!
High prices but the flavors are average. Several other Japanese restaurants are better.

Cosmopolitan atmosphere. Open and airy.  The service was impeccable.   Truly outstanding.  The food was imaginative. We had the price fixe promotion.  And the DC Restaurant week promotion did its job. We drove 45 miles into town to try something new.  We will definitely be back to try some other things on the menu.
Restaurant Week dinner was delicious!!
The food quality is not worth the price. I ordered the A5 wagyu, and it was disappointed.

(Translated by Google) Japanese cuisine is super good at this beautiful restaurant with charm and warm atmosphere.  (Original) Le cuisine japonaise est super bonne à cette belle restaurant avec charme et ambiance chaleureuse.

Must order: spicy tuna with crispy rice, rock shrimp, waguy goyza, and if you really like fish the black cod on lettuce has a mild fish flavor with hints of tea leaves. Of the taco fillings we liked the tuna the most, followed by the lobster. The beef was stringy and old tasting. The service was great. You won’t go wrong with any of the rolls you order but our favorites were the crab and the eel. When we went they had recently lost their pastry chef so the dessert menu was not interesting at all.

I must say, this place does not live up to the hype. I went for happy hour, which offers a less expensive menu of shareable plates and some drink specials, three cocktails and a few beer and wine selections. While the drinks were good, they were not particularly strong, and thus didn't provide a great happy hour value. I liked the sidecar made with Japanese whiskey and the cucumber martini. In addition to the meh drink specials, the food was just not that great. They have "tacos," which seem very reasonably priced at first glance. But then when you get them they are about an inch and a half long. The sushi, at $12 for 2 rolls, was very ordinary and just not what would be expected from a high-end restaurant. The only thing that was good was that the service was friendly, patient, and helpful. But then, the server was also overworked and so drinks would often take quite a while to come out. So overall, a disappointment.
It's DC, not like nobu in Vegas , NYC but good enough. Just as expensive service could be hit or miss , nice decore

Heard good things about Nobu in New York and Vegas, so definitely want to check the one in DC to see if it lives up to its name. Although the restaurant opens at 5:00PM, the host won't allow you sit at the sushi bar or other parts of the restaurant until 6:00PM, so you have to wait by the bar area if you want to be seated on the restaurant side. Instead of waiting for an hour, I decided to just sit by the bar side and ordered the Chef's Omakase.  The good: The food looked was displayed beautifully and it made the dish look delicious! I enjoyed the nigiris, salmon with caviar, and the desserts. The sweet ebi had a good sweetness to it, and the head was crunchy. The nigiri pieces were soft and tasty, and didn't have a lot of rice. The salmon with caviar was delicious. The Panna Cotta dessert was delicious! I would definitely return to order the Panna Cotta.  The bad: Most of the food was salty. Even though it looked delicious, it failed to meet my standard of taste. For the price of Omakase, I was expecting it to exceed expectations considering it's a well known chain. I wouldn't recommend ordering the Omakase. Service was really slow, since we asked multiple waiters for tea, and it took 10 - 15 minutes for it to arrive.  Overall, the presentation is beautiful, but the taste is subpar. Even if the Omakase wasn't pricey, it is not worth ordering. The highlight was the Panna Cotta!
Delicious food good service but very expensive
Chef Ramone the greatest chef in the world! Not just D.C, the world! 👨🏻‍🍳 Anytime you visit D.C, visit Nobu. Everything tasted like the greatest food I’ve ever ate. All hail Chef Ramone the great!

An excellent experience. - Service was professional and attentive. All staff were highly knowledgeable about menu offerings. - Ambiance was lovely. Cool surroundings, gorgeous decor. - Food was exemplary, unique, and flavorful. We tried the signature omakase menu per our server's recommendation and were very pleased. In addition, we got the wagyu foie gras dumplings which are to die for. - Last but not least, parking was a breeze because of valet service. A great plus. Would highly recommend Nobu and we are looking forward to returning.

My family are sushi fanatics and we all really enjoyed the experience here.  The fish is top quality and there are really interesting things to try on the menu. Go off the normal nigiri/sashimi list and try something new here. We were all very happy.
The food and the service were really top notch. The drinks were excellent as well.

The famous name but disappointing. Feels like service is in training. Half a bottle of wines offered on a menu and when we ordered it - they said they don’t carry it and just have not updated the menu. The quality of fish is mostly good , however the main dishes were nothing outstanding. Waiters were too eager to clean up your table and did not leave you to have a peaceful meal.. Nobile is  normally known for the food, ambiance and impeccable service. The decor was the only thing that was worth attention.
Didn’t like any of the food. At almost $150/person we tried multiple items on the menu and still didn’t like anything. Not recommended.
Excellent Japanese fusion restaurant. On the expensive side, but you get great food and service

Love Nobu! I was a huge fan of the original in New York.  The environment is chic and modern, great for a date night or celebration. The  rock shrimp tempura is delicious! I always get the that and the Chilean sea bass in black bean sauce (with a side of white rice). I understand that it can be pricey but the food is great and worth it (every now and then). NY used to have the salmon skin salad and jasmine ice cream that I hope they bring back!
Highly recommended.   Expensive, but worth it.
Amazing flavors with peruvian touches
Excellent dining experience. The staff was very knowledgeable and the food was superb. Highly recommend the grapefruit Martini

Wagyu , Uni and other good sushi selections. I recently got to enjoy a special Omakase here . What a treat . First of the main dish was lobster and it done perfectly . The other main was Wagyu and again perfect and amazing . Buttery ! Also balancing out these epic courses there was truffles and caviar . The sushi course were very good and of course also had the wonderful fatty tuna .Had to admit it was over the top but in a good way ; ). I was also glad to enjoy some nice Japanese Whiskies .
Excellent service and food but it has become a little pricey and I'm not sure why

What's to say? It's Nobu. If you know Nobu, then I found it to be as good as any of the other ones I have dined in - NYNY and both in Las Vegas. It isn't traditional sushi (or traditional anything). It's Japanese-inspired menu items fused with whatever the chef finds interesting.  My advice is to NOT attempt to decode the menu... let your wait person bring you what they suggest and trust them. They will ask you about any dietary preferences and/or restrictions and also about your budget - and will respect both. Just know you aren't getting out of there for less than $100/person.

So WACK, restauranteurs note, when u consider DC, whatever u did to make your name, do the same here. This location is not Nobu we love around the world. DC needs sexy ultra modern inspiring spaces, not more drab conservative interiors. Turn up!!! Don't cater to DC of old, that scene is gone. Nobu interior is so BORING, I was falling asleep at table 😴, nothing like South Beach, Vegas, NYC...snoozefest. High price fish in Grandmas basement is a better experience. People who eat sushi/fusion/seafood a lot know there are atleast 10 better places in this region than here.  Fix interior & cook better food or u will close. Let's not even talk service, took 20min to get drink, average food & wait staff are not genuine, atrocious, super fake. Never again, it's a NObu for me dawg!
Wow does not say enough
Great sushi! Very expensive. Wonderful food.

I was at the bar , service was really bad, not professional at all,  food was excellent five star on that,  I was doing it shopping in the area and I decided to have a drink so? I was with tennis shoes and the bartender looked at me like I was not in the right place,  the important thing is if we have money in our credit card not how we dressed up!!!

Unreal sushi and wagyu. Coolest seats are at bar where service is amazing. Furniture style is a bit industrial and dark. Extremely expensive but since you know that going in that is fine for a treat. Overall awesome.

We had an amazing time here and I think Nobu lived up to it's expectations supremely. Laura was an amazing server and helped us to have a memorable experience. We had a mix of Nobu classics and DC specific items. It's a little bit out of the way but not far from Georgetown and right in the West End. Definitely worth the trip. The atmosphere and music is right on point. We chose the custom menu, with a few requests and mostly full trust in our server. The food hits the spot with a mix of Peruvian and Japanese dining. My only complaint was that the first 5 items were all some sort of carpaccio. While I love this dish, it seemed a little over used, to have the same presentation style. Overall, would recommend to anyone. Will be back and feeling very grateful for the awesome experience and adventure.  My favorite dish was the Chilean sea bass. It was cooked to absolute perfection. Smoky, creamy and delicious.
Very average Japanese food. Sushi Taro is substantially better and more reasonably priced.

Lovely American fusion Sushi-Sashimi experience. Reminiscent of Hawaiian Sushi dishes. Hard working staff. Clean facilities. Excellent presentation. The only improvement I can recommend at this level of service is to help your clients put their coats on at the foyer like in other restaurants of similar caliber in DC.
The sushi is great. But they just raised the happy hour price. Gonna have to go a little less often now.

I love sushi. But this place is only good for one visit. Nobu is well known fusion sushi restaurant in every big city. I haven't tried other locations but this place and it was mediocre experience. Decor was modern and low key. Food was just okay. If you are a authentic sushi lover, you will be disappointed. But if you like the fusion Japanese style this might be good place to dine. Our group of 4 ordered variety of dishes to try. Some fusion dishes and few sushi. We all agreed that the food quality and portions are not compatible with the price. However the waiters were pleasant and service was good.
Overpriced for the service you get. Food took forever, service was snails pace. I know they were understaffed, but the restaurant was empty. The LA and Las Vegas locations are better.
Excellent food! Even better service!

I often have stomach issues after I eat out at restaurants, but after eating at Nobu I felt satisfied and good about what I ate. The sticky rice with spicy tuna was such a creative presentation that was delicious. We tried so many creative dishes. My husband, who normally doesn't eat fish, really enjoyed many fish dishes!
There’s nothing like a belly full of warm sticky rice and sweet fish 🍣 also I’m not a big fan of sushi but I am one now after eating at this place !
Good
Excellent food but the service was subpar
One of the best meals I've ever had
The food is pretty good, but there's food of similar caliber available nearby for a lower price.

I had the best meal of my life here. They accommodated my dairy allergy and my pescatarianism for the omakase (7 course custom meal- chef's choice) and still managed to orchestrate an amazing experience. Wow. Wow. Wow. Not to mention the server knew just about everything there was to know about what we were having. So would love to live at this place.

What a great place to experience true creative Japanese food. The influence of Peru is something amazing. Did the classic set menu and was delighted with endless surprises to the taste buds. Thanks also to Saamir for being a very knowledgeable and attentive server. Well done team for making our last night in DC special.
Good food and nice presentation
Everything is delicious, skip the toro
Wasn’t great. Have been to Vegas, Miami, and NYC Nobu and DCs isn’t good. Love my other visits

Food was fantastic. We did the vegetarian omakase and requested that atleast 1 course  is sushi. Seriously after having that sushi my love for sushi has grown leaps and bounds. Just amazing! All the food we had was great, one odd thing was, in the middle of our course tasting(not the beginning) we got a salad. Dont get me wrong, the salad was great but me and hubby thought it was odd. The reason I gave 4 stars is not the food, it's the service. Our server was callous in explaining the menu to us and it was our first time here. We asked him to recommend vegetarian options and he pointed us to the last page and said that's all we have and left. We went over the menu and saw there were many options to choose from along with the pre-fix. We also did not like how the server got the credit card charger to us, asks for a tip first before swiping the card standing right in front of us (give us some space to go over what we had and how we were served). This is not what we expected from a restaurant like Nobu. We expected top notch service here as it's such a well renowned restaurant with great chef and reputation. I hope they improve the service. Other than that, the food is just phenomenal.
This is probably one of my favorite restaurants. A little bit pricey though. However the food is always as good as before.
Don't waste your time or money.  There are hundreds of great restaurants in DC...patronize them.  Food = mediocre.  Cost = high.  Service = absolutely abysmal.  Tourist trap.

I was extremely disappointed at everything, the food was mediocre, the ambience of restaurant was plain brown wooden room made by first time restaurant designers, the waiting staff were a bit pushy. And I’m not talking about the over priced menu. I would Not recommend it or go again. Thank you!
A "wow" with every bite!
The service and food fabulous

The food is mostly really good, but the prices are high and the portions are small. It’s an expensive night out for two, let alone for any large groups of people (especially if you get drinks). It’s a great experience for one or two times, but it becomes hard to justify going back multiple times for the same foods.
We had a fantastic omakase menu elegantly guided to us by the wonderful Laura! Superbe service, delicious dishes and a good vibe! Definately coming back!!
Best Japanese food I've EVER had HANDS DOWN!!

4.5 stars overall; 5 stars on Foods, 5 stars on services, 4 on beverages, 4 on restroom cleanliness but only deserved a 3 on choices of tables/ chairs & overall layout ( doesn’t look/feel like a luxury/ high-end / top notch restaurant ) However, the Taste Menu is RESLLY a WOW delicious & delightful! 👍👍😋

What a night! Great drinks, great service, beautiful atmosphere, fantastic eats—really enjoyed celebrating my sisters birthday with her & her friends at Nobu D.C.! We were seated quickly and had responses at our table immediately—ALLL of the staff was courteous and friendly, basic service was fulfilled without notice (water glasses refilled without asking, utensils replaced after being utilized for a different part of the meal) The flow of orders could use some help—it would have been better if the kitchen could bring out everyone’s food at one time but the food once you have it, is delectable. Best sushi ever, I don’t think I can eat sushi from anywhere else now! Special shout out to Nicole, Adrian & there’s one more person but I can’t remember his name; but you all work great together seat me in your section anytime!
Great service and yummy food.
Poor service .Good good

I was recently in DC for business and we had a group dinner at Nobu. The menu was pre-set but it was amazing. The service and the food were top notch. I highly recommend Nobu and I plan to visit again so I can try other items from their menu.

Very disappointed. We were chasing down the waitress all night for wine, napkins and additional food orders. We told the waitress about a bad piece of sashimi, but she forgot and we were never offered another option.  When it came time to pay, they bring the card reader to the table and only give you options of 18% gratuity or up, with the waitress hovering over you.  For atmosphere, it felt more like the Jersey Shore than a high end restaurant. They’re proud of the fact that people can wear hats and gym clothes to the restaurant.  This has ended our families respect for the Nobu chain of restaurants. Highly recommend that people look for different options.
Very nice dinner. We had a great time, relaxed, and enjoyable.
The staff was awesome, the food was okay.

Mediocre at best! The service is super slow. The sushi rolls are very basic. I’ve had better sushi at mall food courts than here. I’ve tried Nobu Matsuhisa restaurants in Dubai, Vegas, and London, and had 5 star experience in all of them. This one in DC is damaging the name of this great chain!!!

Cold, hot, and shushi dishes were delicious and exciting, but most of all service was outstanding.  Adrian made great recommendations and made sure we got out in time to get to a show.  I hated to be "those people" but he was very accommodating. Much appreciated!
I have been there twice, both time sat at the bar and  had a great time. Bar tenders know their drinks and the food. Their service is great. Thank you

I found this critically acclaimed Washington, DC restaurant to be lacking in many ways. Prices are extremely high and portion size extremely small. Our service started out well, but halfway into the meal our servers forgot us and it took maybe 15-20 minutes between bringing our courses. We were seated at a table with bright evening sun shining into my eyes... I asked if there was a window shade... there was none. Instead of offering a different table the hostess suggested I switch seats with someone else in our party! The menu selections are quite limited, and most are priced by the "piece". Dinners are all served "family style" with the food placed in the middle of the table and shared by all. We had an $900 bill for 7 people, and I still left hungry.  Never Nobu again for me!!
World class dining experience. From the person who greeted us at the door to our amazing waitress, every staff person went the extra mile to make sure we had an amazing time.
Food was nicely done

Food was a 4 but service from girls at the bar was a 2 so I avg 3 starts seems fair . What is it with the attitude from these 2 ladies wow, talk about not appreciating customers that come spend money in their business, they just don’t get it too bad. Will not recommend
Another great nubu restaurant

My waitress Emma was really sweet.   This restaurant is very vegan friendly and they will alter dishes to fit your dietary needs.   Get the roasted cauliflower and ask for ponzu sauce instead of the jalapeño (there’s milk in it). The mixed green salad is amazing and so is the crispy rice w/ avocado.  My only problem is the kitchen got careless towards the end of our meal... things took way too long to come out or didn’t come out at all.

Overrated. The fish is no better than in the top sushi bars in town so it comes down to, as the servers say, to the "nobu experience ". Unfortunately our experience wasn't all that special - after dutifully asking about any food allergies they proceeded to bring out not one but two different dishes containing the allergen.  If that's the nobu experience I'll save the $500 next time, thanks.
The food is negatively correlated with the price at this establishment.  There is nothing inexpensive there - nothing is worth the price. Just blah...
Way over priced for Sub Par quality . Not worth it unfortunately.
Sushi wrong temp way over prices for the gas station quilty sad
Disgusting!  Cold food and poor service with outrageous prices.  My stomach started hurting as soon as dinner was wrapping up and I threw up two hours after eating there.  YUCK!
Overpriced food didn't test good.
The yellowtail tuna with jalapeno is to die for. The customer service was excellent too.

The quality of the food was average, and did not live up to the omakase price. The wait staff were very pushy and patronizing. Therefor, need more training. We are very upset to see the Nobu brand being dialuted.
Outstanding service by the waiter and the other staff.
Fake and contrived
Worst experience ever I will never return
Matsuhisa Aspen (also a Nobu venture)  is much better. Service is slow and the menu not as interesting
Food not as good expected for the prices. The black cod was over cooked and dry as a bone. The portion sizes and service left us walking hungry out the door. Too bad!

I only had dessert and it was breathtaking. Something to do with coffee, Carmel and hazelnuts. I would totally order it again as the mix of flavors, textures and temperatures was unexpected however I wish it wasn't ~$20 a plate
The food was good but way overpriced. The five us spent $800 and left hungry, we ordered a pizza when we got home.

We were concerned as this is iteration number 30 something... and then there was that Post review... BUT, having been to the Nobu in NYC we decided to go and try. We were so glad we did. The food was really excellent and we were so focused on it, the service was not much on our radar. That said, we thought the service was fine and not overbearing, but we were not ignored. Definitely good for a date or dinner with friends! We did the chef's tasting menu, which always proves to be an adventure. We had some combinations we never thought we'd see that were sublime. And the tuna sashimi was so good I closed my eyes while I ate it and tried to savor it for as long as humanly possible. The waitress and bartender were helpful in pairing sake with our meal. The restaurant is nice looking and rather large, though the ceilings seem low. It is definitely bustling. A fun place and more importantly, a decadent, delicious foodie destination.
Excellent Japanese food.
Great food and great music
Not the same as NYC

Ordered bento and garlic scallop. Great destination if you come on a weekday for lunch. Quiet and not so intimidating. However, you can’t really go anywhere upscale in DC without hearing people talk about Trump/politics.
Peruvian influence really makes the diffrence. Best Japanesse restaurant in the area.
Amazing.  Phenomenal food and service. Our server waitress was wonderful and very knowledgeable and attentive.

My husband and I went here as a recommendation from a friend, the restaurant was very classy and the lighting dim, the service was amazing with Valet parking and the food delicious. We would definitely go again, we sat at the sushi bar because we didn’t make reservations it was still a very classy place.
Fantastic sushi.
The attention to detail and service was fantastic. One the top restaurants in DC. The price may give some a bit of sticker shock, but the value is worth the experience.
Food was incredible! Truly great sushi, and some very inventive dishes that you can't just get anywhere. Service and atmosphere were solid. Pricing was totally reasonable.
Very expensive. Not up to the usual Nobu quality.
Food is good. I had better sushi than this so I can’t say this is best I had . Service s ok too sometimes it feels they are a little lost
Washingtonian said it best "...it doesn't matter"
Great sushi and drinks
Love Nobu, but the one in DC does not have the same quality as other locations.

I frequent Nobu's on a regular basis and this is an interesting one.  I am goodly familiar with Washington, DC and found the area that this is located in to be unexpected.  It seems like it is in a residential neighborhood, fairly close to Historic Georgetown.  That said, there was no valet and we ended up walking from several blocks away, which given the weather was an annoyance.  Ambience inside reminded me of an asia food court.  We came in and rather then wait for a table we ended up sitting at the bar to dine.  This is what made our night.  I have been at Nobus all across the world, London, Munich, Milan, etc and regulary dine at Michelin starred restaurants and have never had better service then with your bartender Michael.  He reminded me of a movie bartender, fit, handsome and was seemed very intelligent and well read.  Our discussion varied about different spirits, then about the difference between wagyu and washu, and listened to him speak with the couple next to us about how King Phillip was the only reason Alexander ever had the opportunity to be great.  Very fun night and quite an education with him, he made our night.   As for the food, it was less then what I expected when I come to Nobu and the Wagyu dumpling were much to greasy for me.  Food came out in the right order, but seemed to take longer between some courses.   Overall experience was excellent, due to service.
A level of culinary decadence that can't be matched. The sashimi will have you craving more.
Food was great.  Atmosphere is great. Nobu is just awesome.
Overpriced and over rated
Amazing service really felt cared for the food fantastic and the atmosphere awesome thank you nobu dc will always remember the experience
Good place

This was an disappointing experience since I has been to the NY and Miami location. The service and food was about average and not worth the money.  Waiting time for just a menu and water was unbelievable.
Great food, nice bar, attentive service.
Great service. Fine food, extremely overpriced

This is a first!  I’m writing this review about Nobu-DC without even having been there yet!  We have been to Nobu in Vegas, and San Diego! Both locations were great and so we were happy when the DC location opened. Made reservations to go there for early dinner on a Friday evening, but on the day of, I received a call from the restaurant confirming the reservations, but also reminding us that we have to be done by a certain time because of their second seating!   This was a first for me; I can honestly say that I have never had any place do that.  To me, that is the opposite of hospitality: do you ask your guests when they are leaving before they arrive??? The girl on the phone was unable to answer that question!  As far as I’m concerned, no restaurant is worth it; certainly not Nobu. This kind of (non) service, even before one arrives, can only mean one thing, worse service once you get there. So, I canceled our reservations and we’re happy to take our appetites and money somewhere where they’ll be appreciated!

Great food, but severely overpriced, it cost the two of us $630 for food and drinks and i was still really hungry at the end. The food was awesome and the cocktails were different and great but i've had better for literally half the price in chefs hat restaurants in Australia, which is renowned for being one of the most expensive countries in the world!

Nice buildout and food generally consistent with New York and Vegas but the other issues overshadow the food, hence the two stars.  After a debacle with our bill and an incompetent waiter who overcharged us by “creating a family style dining experience”, (one of us charged $350 while two others $120 and $200 for the same size portion/entree I ordered for myself so 1 order split for 3 people) we complained to the manager and were given a $200 credit for another shot at dining there.  Well, same results: food was good and service not so much.   Food came out inconsistently and while one of us got a plate, everyone else sat there waiting for long periods of time with nothing.  Entrees came out for others while a few hadn’t even received their starters.  Bottom line, they said that’s how the kitchens works.  What?  Not acceptable.  I’ve been to other Nobu locations and by far, the staff seemed not to standard of price point of Nobu and the inconsistency and confusion over our orders left us frustrated.  I won’t return to the DC location.  Will be interested to see if this Nobu makes it in this government town.
Poor service.  Will not be going back any time soon.
Customer service was great! Food lacks taste but presentable. Nothing like Vegas or NY
Food is mediocre, drinks were decent. Unlikely to return.
Ok, I've been to many Nobu restaurants and appreciate the high quality experience. It's pretty pricey however.
The Ambiance was unique to the DC scene  Sushi bar was backed up  Overall not bad
The food was good but our server was deceptive.  Ruied the experience.
Very big disappointment in comparison to the NYC Nobu!! Lacks ambiance and staff needs to be more polished.

There's sushi l and then there is NOBU!!!...there are no words befitting of the  description .....this place takes sushi to a level you have never seen..the only downside is PARKING...go early!!!..oh, reservations are out at least a week!!!.plan early!!!..but you can always sit at the bar!!

Sorry to say, I was pretty disappointed... when I heard that Nobu DC was opening in October I was uber excited to celebrate my birthday there. I've dined at Nobu Miami and Nobu Las Vegas and to say the least Nobu D.C. just doesn't compare. To start there is no valet available. After circling the block several times we found a space a block away. When we entered the building how surprised/disappointed was I to find that that restaurant doesn't have the Asian theme that the other locations have. Therefore, ambience just isn't the same.  We had reservations so we were seated very quickly. We had a table for two but the tables were so close that I had to excuse myself to slide between our table and the neighbors not to bump it. We could have just been seated together at a 4 top table. Once seated the first thing I noticed was the disposable wooden chopsticks that needed to be pulled from the paper and snapped apart in order to be used. I have had better chopsticks from a hole in the wall Chinese restaurant at gallery place/China town. Also, the wait staff at this location is dressed more casual than what I remember at the other locations. Although they wear black shirts and pants they didn't have the jackets or ties that the other locations wear. After asking if we had dined at Nobu before the waiter offered us the Nobu traditional ordering style which we agreed to. It's a process where they ask you a few questions to familiarize themselves with your flavor palette and food preferences and they come up with a dining menu for your table. Everything was just fine until he asked the final question... "my final question is, what is your price point for this meal?" "Excuse me??" I asked. He went on to explain that some items are market priced and he didn't want to exceed our budget. Needless to say, I was appalled.  I reassured him that we were prepared to pay for all items that are served and then reiterated that this was NOT our first time dining at Nobu.  We ordered Edamame; King Crab Tempura; Miso Chilean Sea bass; 4oz of Wagu beef, and a side of Miso Wild Mushrooms. The food took a while to come out but it was good. Again not the best I've had from Nobu and by the time we got to the food I was so disappointed that I just wanted to eat quickly and move on with our evening to my next birthday festivity. I will not be coming back. I would rather fly 2hrs  to Miami have dinner and come back the same day than to dine there again.
We did the Chef special and for the money...was slightly underwhelmed. But the Chilean sea bass was TO DIE FOR.
I had read the bad reviews and went anyway. Big mistake. Space was drab. Felt like I was eating at a picnic table In a warehouse. Black cod was flavorless. If you must go, order the ginger cocktail.

This is not the Nobu of the quality in NY or Vegas. Very disappointing.  I would not recommend it.  The signature dish of the miso cod was below average. The sushi was very mediocre.  The fish tacos were good, but very small.  The only positive was the signature cocktail.

Overpriced, terrible service, mediocre drinks, mediocre food (and 1 dish that was partially inedible).  Dreary decor but finally a DC restaurant where everyone isn’t packed in like sardines.  With so many other good dining options in DC I don’t see myself returning to Nobu.  I recommend spending your hard earned money elsewhere.
I went there last week with some friends, it was outstanding experiences from the time we walked in to the time we left. Coming back here again for my wife birthday tonight.
Honestly, the best sushi I’ve tasted in a long while. Nice staff. Great ambiance. Interesting people watching... great lighting. Totally a 5 star restaurant imo

This  was my 1st time eating at Nobu in any location. The hype for the food was way overblown, or so I thought, but to my genuine surprise it had not been. The whole dining experience from the moment we walked through the door to the time we departed, it was a wonderful evening. The staff were courteous and very attentive to our every need. The timing of the food was impeccable, as our plate was finished and cleared away, a new one would arrive with a wonderful explanation of the new dish. I would like to praise the Bar Manager Thuy Hong who helped us in our selection of dishes, from a very nice menu. Everything chosen was perfectly presented and tasted wonderful of the seven plates we chose, it was to difficult to pick a winner. Will definitely be going back.

Ate at Nobu in Malibu a couple months ago, and was super excited that a DC location would be opening soon.  Had dinner at the new locale tonight, and it was fantastic. Japanese Peruvian cuisine sounds odd, but Nobu is a genius melding of spice and sushi. All of the sashimi is amazing! And the edamame appetizer, again with the spice, was inventive and tasty. But the crispy rice was a little chewy/gummy, and the lobster tacos didn't have much flavor. I also discovered that I don't like raw scallops, but that's not Nobu's fault. Their signature cocktail, the "25th & M",  is delicious - tequila, dill, habanero... who would think of this combo?! So good! I will definitely be going back there for special occasions. I don't understand the reviews that are critical of the neighborhood and the building. It's located on the edge of Georgetown, which I appreciate - less pedestrian traffic and not a nightmare to drive there.  It's in the ground floor of a typical DC office building, nothing warehouse-y about it. The interior is spacious, not too noisy, and the tables are not butted up against each other, which I also appreciate. Shout out to our server, Matthew! Terrific energy, and expert guidance on our menu choices. Thank you!

We waited 1.5 hours for sushi. I'm extremely disappointed and I won't be back,  I love the way me in Malibu, but the dc location is disorganized. However, the wait service is phenomenonal and very kind.

Nobu is a terrible disappointment.  The staff seems highly disorganized and the design layout, especially the bar area, is pretty terrible.  Do yourself a favor and go to Himitsu instead, which does everything Nobu tries to do, but significantly better and cheaper.

No Noboo, no. A 5* name with a rather less than spectacular establishment- a chain that's a status symbol. Nobu who is now about 70 years old probably has nothing to do with the restaurants themselves.  Our server was a nice guy but overwhelming. He was pushy to the point it got really annoying and unpleasant. We tried several things and everytime we ordered one of each, he would say "Are you sure you don't want 2? It's only 1 piece, are you sure?". Um yeah dude, we're sure. He also didn't know the answers to a lot of my questions and had to run and ask the chef. They tried so hard here that it became intrusive and confusing. But hey, it's opening week- service can and most the time does improve so let's move past all this and onto what's important, the food!  Most wasabi in America is a mixture of ingredients that is designed to replicate the taste of real wasabi. Usually horseradish & food coloring. Tonight it was horseradish & wasabi powder. Awesome. No, really- it was "awesome".  Nigiri is one type of sushi that should be eaten with your hands and not your chopsticks. You should never dip the rice portion into soy sauce so you don't overpower the seasoning of the rice. It's my favorite type. People focus on the quality of the fish in producing sushi- but it's the sushi rice that really matters the most. Sushi rice should be served body temperature, not room temperature or chilled. When you get substandard rice, you're not getting a quality sushi experience. Nobu's rice was a dissapointment. It was a little mushy and a bit sweet. So what did I do that I never do?! Dip it in soy sauce! Because sodium makes everything that doesn't taste good taste better. The mediocre quality of the fish didn't help either. I was sad, like a boy who was so excited to go to a candy store only to not get candy. Because sushi is not what I received.  All the other dishes were all subpar. The tempura had too much batter, the shitake mushroom salad tasted like something I get 3 times a week at Modern Market, lobster ceviche was good but there was 2 bites to it, the tacos- now these bad boys were literally the size of a nacho for $10 (but they were good, my favorite part of the night but surely not worth it), the shrimp tempura roll was great- I enjoyed it, the vegetable roll was utterly tasteless (Wholefoods does it better and that's sad), eggplant was eggplant with sweet sauce on top, and miso soup was salty. Most restaurant can't make a good miso soup anyhow so I didn't expect much.  But hey- go, do it, try it, so you can tell all your friends you went to Nobu. But keep your expectations low and your wallet loaded. For you shall spend what is known as "hard earned money" so you can leave saying no to NoBoo.
